Comment: Another post-neo noir gem that slipped through the cracks in 2018 and got minimal recognition in the public. This is a great movie. I especially liked the dualism presented in the film in "allegorical" style as Billie Lee suggested. Right (Rosie) and Wrong (the Sister), Rosie (Weak) vs Emily (Strong-willed), the line between Nevada and California, the singer vs the juke box, the fake priest (Jeff Bridges) vs the cultist Messiah (Chris Hemsworth), the rain vs the sunshine, the listening bugs vs the camera, the motel rooms (light) vs the secret corridor of (darkness).

Title: Bad Times at the El Royale | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment: A modern homage to film noir. A strong cast, solid film making, great soundtrack, and plot makes Bad Times At The El Royale worth a watch for fans of the genre. It's dark, very violent, and a bit surreal. Rare to see a movie like this in modern times, where reboots of garbage are the norm. The cast took a pay cut to make this movie knowing it could be something above the typical junk that passes for movies these days. Per usual, Jeff Bridges is a scene stealer being a master of his craft. Quentin Tarantino could have made this film if he were a better director... The ending drags some and gets predictable and formulaic, but it does not ruin an otherwise strong movie. This film deserves to be seen if for no other reason to send the message (and $ is always the message they wanna hear) we want more original movies that take a chance. A-

Comment:
A really well-written and well-directed thriller. A mind boggling film with heart captivating scenes.

Not too overly complicated, therefore easy to follow and interpret the storyline. The star of the show or shall I say the person that stole the show, has to be indeed Lewis Pullman's, Miles Milner. 

Pullman's acting was strongly convincing, geniune, and full of quality. Not intentionally undermining the performance of the remaining cast, but Pullman for me gave this film the magic touch it needed through his performance (especially the ending), and you will also agree why I say this when you watch the movie.
